As shown in Fig. 4b, the excitation-independent phosphorescence spectrum of CA-MA-3 has four emission peaks at 387, 407, 458 and 486 nm under the optimal excitation at 270 nm, indicating that different radiative transition paths may exist in the composite. Compared with the fluorescence emission of 470 nm, the RTP emission center of CA-MA-3 presented a red-shifted maximum at 486 nm. Pure MA exhibits the phosphorescent emission at 454 nm under excitation at 270 nm, and its brightness is much lower than that of CA-MA-3 under the same condition (Figs. S8b and S9). At the same time, MA-A has a powerful phosphorescence with a maximum emission of 498 nm (Fig. 4c). It was observed that different solid samples including CA-MA-3, CA-MA-4, MA-A (200 °C, 6 h), MA-B (200 °C, 3 h), MA-D (150 °C, 6 h) and CACDs@MA obtained by hydrothermal method also exhibited excellent RTP emission (Fig. S10). The CA-MA-3 powder emits blue-green fluorescence and yellow-green RTP under 365 nm excitation at room temperature. Meanwhile, as shown in Fig. 5
                     a, the afterglow can last 4 s to the naked eyes after turning off the 365 nm UV lamp. We further investigated the phosphorescence of the composite material CA-MA (Fig. S11). The results show that a distinct blue RTP emission band appears at 370–420 nm during the in situ formation of CACDs in CA-MA composites, and the RTP intensities increased first and then decreased, reaching a maximum for CA-MA-3 with a molar ratio of MA/CA = 2:1. The decrease in RTP intensity for the composites CA-MA-4 and CA-MA-5 compared with CA-MA-3 may be due to the aggregation of in situ generated CDs derived from CA in the crystals at the excitation wavelength of 270 nm (Fig. S12a). We speculated that the dual channel RTP emission process for CA-MA composites should come from CACDs (370–420 nm) and MA-derived crystal matrix (450–550 nm) (Scheme 1
                     ) [45,62].
